
```suggestion
`p ‚Ü¶ p.derivSeries` and currying suitably. It is defined so that, if a function `p` has a power
```

Apparently [This answer](https://math.stackexchange.com/a/69231/12932) says that a C^1 function on a Banach space over ‚ÑÇ is already analytic, but it seems Mathlib only knows the 1-dimensional case. And it seems you didn't need completeness in this PR ...

The point of the PR is a little bit different: We already have the statement over R or C (assuming C^2), and I want to extend it to other fields (assuming analyticity, because otherwise it's not true). You are correct that one could do better over C (where C^1 implies analytic) but I don't think it would really be useful to state it in this way (because, after all, the C^1 functions over C are already analytic, so the current lemma applies).

"larger than" tends to evoke associations "larger at not equal" (as opposed to e.g. "at least").
This may be entirely subjective, but I would personally prefer "at least n".

It's getting late, and my brain stared at this for too long. To ensure I got it: this lemma makes sense over general fields, because the \infty stands for "smooth, but not analytic", right?

Perhaps a comment is useful. Up to you.
